cff-version: 1.2.0
message: >
  If you reference this work in academic publications, technical
  reports, or comparative AI research, please cite as follows.
title: >
  adam — deterministic AI research kernel for agglutinative
  languages (Qazaq IR)
abstract: >
  adam is the applied demonstrator of Qazaq IR — a deterministic
  alternative to probabilistic large language models, built on the
  agglutinative-morphology algebra of the Kazakh language. The
  research investigates whether agglutinative languages can serve
  as the substrate for AI systems with three architectural
  guarantees: predictability (every output traceable to a curated
  source), cheapness (single-binary deployment, 0% GPU,
  ~21 ms p50 latency, ~300 MB RSS), and safety (architectural
  impossibility of hallucination — the runtime cannot emit a claim
  without backing fact in the curated knowledge graph). The
  approach generalises across the ~30 catalogued agglutinative
  languages (Turkish, Korean, Japanese, Finnish, Hungarian, Tamil,
  Quechua, Swahili, …). adam currently demonstrates the
  architecture as a Kazakh-language Rust-programming tutor.
